# ⚠ REFERENCE COPY — THE SERVER DOES NOT RUN THIS FILE.
#
# The live front door is the Lens stack's containerised Caddy: the file Caddy
# actually reads is  talyvor-lens/deploy/caddy/Caddyfile  (mounted read-only
# into the compose `caddy` service). Editing THIS file changes nothing on the
# server — make front-door changes there, then reload the container
# (deploy/README.md §7). This copy exists so the suite repo records what the
# talyvor site blocks should say.
#
# Because Caddy is a container, the BFF is reached over the Docker bridge —
# host.docker.internal (requires `extra_hosts: ["host.docker.internal:
# host-gateway"]` on the caddy service), NOT 127.0.0.1: inside the container,
# loopback is the container itself, and a loopback target fails with
# "dial tcp 172.17.0.1:8787: i/o timeout".
#
# The BFF side of this contract (see apps/bff and deploy/README.md §4):
#   BFF_ADDR=0.0.0.0:8787                          ← bridge-reachable; ufw scopes
#                                                    :8787 to 172.16.0.0/12
#   BFF_AUTH_MODE=oidc                             ← the ONLY mode that permits a
#                                                    non-loopback bind…
#   BFF_PUBLIC_BASE_URL=https://app.talyvor.com    ← …and only with an https
#                                                    public origin. Also derives
#                                                    the OIDC redirect URI and
#                                                    scopes the __Host- cookie.
# The BFF refuses to start if that posture is inconsistent (see loadConfig).

# The apex 301s to the app host. Assumes talyvor.com's DNS points at this
# server — which is what makes the redirect work.
talyvor.com {
	redir https://app.talyvor.com{uri} 301
}

app.talyvor.com {
	# The session cookie only ever travels over TLS (it is __Host-/Secure);
	# pin browsers to https for the host outright.
	header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000"

	reverse_proxy host.docker.internal:8787
}
